Secondly not understanding that with the new legislation super accounts (not pension accounts) will be the main withdrawl method for living expenses. Withdrawal processes in super need to be updated for regular payments etc. Currently there is only a costly lump sum withdrawal process. This is surprising as many of your competitors are using this as a marketing tool.

Don't feel special, you are all as bad as each other. The only saving grace is that many of the problems are possibly due to poor government legislation. I certainly hope so, otherwise you are worse than I think. My specific problem relates to the fact that we "must have" a super account even when undertaking casual employment, particularly for short periods of time. So the miniscule amount of money is rapidly eaten away by "management" fees, $1.50 per day in your case. That is about $550 over 12 months. Most of us working a seasonal harvest would not make that much! There needs to be a special category super account for casual seasonal workers which is more like a bank account. The money goes in, it is less than the prescribed minimum, I am over retirement age, so I can withdraw the lot (before you do). There are no charges, you get to use the money whilst you have it, then I get at least the contributions back. Then it is there for next year. Saves you money too because at the moment, I close the account, then open a new one next year and you have to go through all the expense of setting up a new account, sending out paperwork, etc, etc, etc. Try thinking outside the square! Difficult for bean counters I know, but try.
